I went here for my 2 year anniversary and while it turned out to be the most expensive meal I've ever had, I'd still have to say that it was an absolute bargain given what we had and, as many other yelpers have commented, worth every penny! Not only was the service absolutely fantastic and friendly, but the food was simply amazing! Every course made my tastebuds jump to life: the oysters were orgasmic, the foie gras was beyond rich, and ooooooh, the cheeses! It really was a dining experience and I can't wait to go back again!

The food was awesome, the quality of service was awesome, the price was pretty awesome for everything that you get. Did I mention the service was fantastic? I recently decided to go to Fleur de Lys for my birthday because I could not get reservations at Danko's two months in advance! I really should've gone somewhere else instead of Fleur de Lys. I was not impressed with that place at all. After dining at Gary Danko's, you might have very high expectations for other fine dining restaurants. I ordered the fois gras as my appetizer- delicious delicious delicious! And there was so much of it! My main course was the main lobster. Looked much smaller than a main lobster, but the sauce it was sitting in was absolutely magnificent. I tasted other's dishes and they were all very good. If you order the creme brulee for dessert, be prepared to not be able to finish it. It's pretty ridiculous! 3 large creme brulees of different flavors... Who could eat that much after eating all of the other food. The meal was surprisingly very filling. And I have a pretty big appetite. I was stuffed at the end of the meal. Don't fill yourself up with too much bread. You won't be able to finish your dessert!

So very good, but so very expensive. I got the Lobster Risotto, Seared Tuna, Loin of Lamb and the French Macaroon Ice Cream Sandwiches for dessert. My fiance got the Lobster Risotto, Herb Crusted Salmon, Filet of Beef and the Chocolate Souffle for dessert. Everything was absolutely divine, and the sommelier helped us pair a few of the dishes with different wines. The ambiance was perfect, and the service was impeccable. The only reason I am giving Restaurant Gary Danko 4 stars (as opposed to 5 stars) was that after making reservations exactly 2 months out for a Saturday night dinner, reading rave reviews and expecting to have a surreal dining experience, I walked away from there thinking, "That was really good." I had expected, "Wow, that was one of the greatest meals I've ever had!" Oh well--perhaps I had just psyched myself out a bit too much. I've had the Gary Danko experience, and I definitely recommend this restaurant for all you Bay Area foodies! Book early! Side Note: We valet parked with the restaurant, and even though we gave the waiter our ticket when we took care of the bill, the car still was not outside when we exited the restaurant. (About 15 minutes elapsed.) It was very windy and cold, and I figured the valet service could have been more prompt.

My family and I come to Gary Danko maybe once or twice a year, for a special occasion like a birthday or anniversary. It's hard to get a reservation, and for good reason. FIrst off, the service is amazing! You're greeted instantly and you feel like you belong there. People immediately take your coats and seat you. Offered for the ladies are purse hooks, a really nice touch. When I went to the bathroom, I was pointed to the right direction. In fact, the last time I was dining at GD with the fam, there was apparently a longggg line for the bathroom so a waitress showed me to another bathroom that was unoccupied and no line :) Got back to the table before my sister and mom, who both went to the restroom before me. Hehe. The wait staff also always take your napkin and fold it up for you, waiting upon your return. Totally unnecessary but proof of complete attentiveness. One of my favorite parts of the people at GD's is how much they care for the customer. My family and I were running late for our reservation, probably 15-20 minutes late, and we weren't rushed at all during our meal. In fact, they reassured us there was no rush to gobble down food or anything. It's nice to not feel the pressure in such a high-end restaurant, where people are always trying to get in. Snobby? Don't think so. So Gary Danko has the whole 3-4-5 courses to choose from. It can be a combo of ANYTHING. From a dish from each section of the menu to a meal consisting of only dessert. They time it all so that no matter what people order, whether one person gets three courses while the other gets five, you will all finish at the same time. Love the flexibility. If you go to other restaurants, they require that everyone orders the tasting menu or everyone has to order off the a la carte menu I've got to say that I love the food here. Haven't been disappointed yet. My favorite has got to be the ahi tuna. Fresh, and comes with avocados! Yummm. The lobster risotto is pretty good too. Never ordered it but swooped a couple of bites from my family members hehehe. Delish but can't beat out my ahi tuna. Now i have horrible memory and can't remember what else I usually order but I do remember ordering the pork belly the last time. I thought I should try it and stop ordering the usual steaks/fish. I was a little iffy, and asked the waiter for his opinion and he said it's one of his favorites. Warning him that I'm not as adventurous with my palette as others may be, he said "Don't worry. You've had bacon? Then you've had pork belly." That was something new I learned haha. So I got it and was extremely pleased. Tender and wonderful and flavorful. Just proves to me (and maybe others haha) that no matter how foreign (or not) something may be, it'll probably be damn good here. I've also gotten the horseradish salmon medallion. Oh god I love it. It's fresh and has the firmness that at least I love. Still tender enough to fall apart with ease though. It's definitely a unique flavor. It's something I usually get. Now the desserts. All yummy. My parents usually get the chocolate souffles, the star dessert. They pour in 2 sauces, chocolate and something white, I don't know cause I'm too engrossed in how good it looks to ever listen to what it is, but man it's heaven. Another good dessert was the one my sister got. Some delicious spin on an apple pie. Louisiana something yummy with ice cream yum yum yum. I think you all get my drift. YUM! They also end the night giving the ladies delicious breakfast pastries. They're always a different flavor. Sometimes chocolate, other times a fruity flavor, like pineapple. No matter what, it's all yummy.

Yelp should raise the bar and provide 6 stars instead of 5, as Gary Danko deiniftely deserves a 6-star rating. I'm not a regular customer as I've been there only four times in the past 8 years. I would go there only for special occasions. I believe that a good restaurant should come in full package, that includes the atmosphere, the quality of food, and service. Gary Danko has topped all three elements in my book and I will explain why. I chose this place to propose to my wife back in 2000. I realized that proposing is such an important event in my (and our) life so I made a very careful choice after doing tons of research on the web. I don't want to get into too much detail and try to make the long story short. As soon as I called a month ahead to book the reservation, and stated my intention to propose to my wife, the reservationist immediately gave the phone over to the restaurant manager (or head captain). They carefully noted what my expectations, and gave me some advice. Needless to say, the whole event went smoothly and thanks to the staff member of Gary Danko, to orchestrated everything so well. My wife was very touched and agreed to marry me. I remember receiving a bottle of champagne from an old couple eating at the bar, and a nice plate of chocolate, complimentary from the manager. It was a wonderful feeling. Food - Although we've been there only a few times but we have never been disappointed, not a single time. If you watch Iron Chef shows, and it's apparent that you know what good food is supposed to be. The taste, the originality, plating, and presentation. Not a single bit that I can criticize at all. We always try the tasting menu so we can try a little bit of everything, and I suggest you to do the same. Service - staff have been very attentive, yet, not intrusive. Whenever you need anything. Before your eye balls start looking around, the wait person is already next to you, but you never get the feeling that you are being "watched" while you're eating. At least I didn't. Atmosphere - Okay, here's the tough part. The first two times we went, the place was busy (well, always busy) but the noise level was very low and comfortable. However, the last two times (once in 2005 and the other time was in May 2007) were much noisier than it used to be. I don't know if this bothers you, but I feel more comfortable in eating in a nice restaurant without raising my voice to converse. Having said that, this does NOT cloud my intention to give Gary Danko a 6 star rating. Hope this is helpful to you. If you're well off, you should go there often. If you're just like me, a normal working class employee, you should eat there at least once. - jcgoobee -

Gary Danko is a very special place. Few restaurants can combine brilliant cuisine, extraordinary service, and such a beautiful environment. First, the dishes are lush, beautiful to observe, and thoughtfully prepared. For our last dinner, we began with the glazed oysters. The oysters are tender, and the cavier lends a deeply rich taste that is not heavy, but suprisingly light. We had both a lobster salad with a hazelnut compote, and a roaster lobster over potato with what I beleive was a truffle oil though I may be mistaken. Both were artfully prepared, and the lobster was tender and very flavorful. The dishes wind together classic elements with innovative features, such as the aforementioned hazlenut. Ingredients are very fresh, and the preparations are deceptively complex. Try a green bean off of your plate. Now try one from another dish. Yes, they are very, very different, each matched to the context of the plate they are served on. The artful presentation of the food is also delightful. Separate ceramic dishes are used, many finely crafted with striking designs. The food and its presentation are truly an integrated whole. Our belini was serviced on a sparklying black dish that I could have easily made the center piece of a table is was so pleasing to the eye. The restaurant itself is a jewel box, with interesting artwork abounding on the walls, and incredible flower arrangement in unusual glass vases. Its simply fun to look around and take in your surroundings. Finally, the service is amazing. Small touches you may not notice are present everywhere. For example, when they pour wine, the bottle is *always* held so that you can see the label and know what is moving into your glass. If your date needs to excuse herself/himself as a dish is being set down, they will immediately cover it with a beautiful silver warmer (they'll hold it if its not already placed until she/he returns). The roses on the table are very pretty and add a touch of elegence. The waitstaff lets you take your time with the menu, knows its contents thoroughly, and is friendly and welcoming without crowding you. The amazing thing is how effortless this whole process appears, when in fact, it must take the discipline and coordination of a full submarine crew to run the place. Steven Lande, their manager, is a welcoming host. I have no idea how he manages the operation, but whatever he is doing, it works incredibly well. None of the top notch restaurants I've tried in even the most service intensive places (e.g. Hong Kong) can match what his team delivers. I should also add that all of my friends here have been made to feel welcome, irrespective of who they are. I was concerned that being in my late twenties when I first tried the restauranta few years ago that I might not be treated well--quite the opposite, I was made to feel very welcome. Likewise, my gay friends, asian friends, and african american friends have all felt they received top flight service. Its a place you can take your parents, your wife/girlfriend/partner, or a group of buddies and enjoy a truly terrific dinner. Love it!

RATING - 4 1/2 stars. This review is based on one visit only. I'm looking forward to returning for more! SERVICE - Excellent across the board. Baked Chocolate Souffle with Two Sauces - 4 1/2 stars Lemon Mousse (complimentary birthday dessert) - 4 stars My husband really enjoyed his venison and lobster risotto, though his favorite was the roast crab. I recently dined at Gary Danko for the second time--both times were on the firm's tab so I offer no thoughts about pricing and other indelicacies. I like Danko. I do. Both meals I had were very good. Last week's meal (4 courses) included: the rare tuna with avocado and lemon soy dressing, the seared sea scallops with gava beans, frisee and prosciutto, the beef filet with blue cheese butter, and the cheese course. During the meal, I found out that a business associate had recently had a birthday so I feigned a trip to the loo and notified a server (not "our" server since at least 6 different people made stops at our table over the course of the night). I am so pleased to revise my 2-star review of Restaurant Gary Danko, from 2001! That review was granted after two consecutive dining experiences that were far less than the price and reputation warranted. On this outing, perfection was the watch word. The silent, near-invisible ballet troup tended to our needs in a finely choreographed ensemble. They earned every one of the little gold pins they wear on their lapels. And the staff managed the perfect balance between professionalism and friendliness. And they clearly love great food - a passion that is contagious. We brought two bottles of our own special wine selected specifically for our friend's 50th birthday, and the $35 corkage fee seems more than reasonable given the lost revenue from their extensive wine list. The sommelier (I just noticed the Yelp! Spell Checker wants to substitute the word "smellier" for "sommelier"!) added to this perfect score, keeping both of our special wines at the perfect serving temperature and decanting our old red wine perfectly, as one would expect, shortly before serving. Kudos!

This is our go-to fine dining restaurant whenever we have a chance to come out to the city. The food never seems to disappoint. I actually think this is the best in SF. Instead of waiting 3 months for a reservation, we got in within 3 weeks (midweek tho). I started off with the Fois Gras and Rhubarb- always delicious but the Fois Gras was a little tiny. Rhubarb was actually very soft and complimented the dish. My husband ordered the Soft Shell Crab- BEST DISH OF THE NIGHT! It was lightly fried but to the point where the shell was tasteless and perfect. The meat was soft, sweet and succulent! I agree with the other review....my complimentary Bday Lemon Mousse cheesecake dessert was better than my chocolate souffle. My husband very much enjoyed his creme brulee trio, as he is a creme brulee LOVER! I can't wait to come back here with friends!

The food and service are top-notch. This is definitely a place to go for a special occasion but to me, the delicious food, outstanding service, and attention to detail warrant the steep price. One of the best (if not the best) meals I have ever had.

    My family and I come to Gary Danko maybe once or twice a year, for a special occasion like a birthday or anniversary. It's hard to get a reservation, and for good reason.

    FIrst off, the service is amazing! You're greeted instantly and you feel like you belong there. People immediately take your coats and seat you. Offered for the ladies are purse hooks, a really nice touch. When I went to the bathroom, I was pointed to the right direction. In fact, the last time I was dining at GD with the fam, there was apparently a longggg line for the bathroom so a waitress showed me to another bathroom that was unoccupied and no line :) Got back to the table before my sister and mom, who both went to the restroom before me. Hehe. The wait staff also always take your napkin and fold it up for you, waiting upon your return. Totally unnecessary but proof of complete attentiveness.

    One of my favorite parts of the people at GD's is how much they care for the customer. My family and I were running late for our reservation, probably 15-20 minutes late, and we weren't rushed at all during our meal. In fact, they reassured us there was no rush to gobble down food or anything. It's nice to not feel the pressure in such a high-end restaurant, where people are always trying to get in. Snobby? Don't think so.

    So Gary Danko has the whole 3-4-5 courses to choose from. It can be a combo of ANYTHING. From a dish from each section of the menu to a meal consisting of only dessert. They time it all so that no matter what people order, whether one person gets three courses while the other gets five, you will all finish at the same time. Love the flexibility. If you go to other restaurants, they require that everyone orders the tasting menu or everyone has to order off the a la carte menu

    I've got to say that I love the food here. Haven't been disappointed yet. My favorite has got to be the ahi tuna. Fresh, and comes with avocados! Yummm. The lobster risotto is pretty good too. Never ordered it but swooped a couple of bites from my family members hehehe. Delish but can't beat out my ahi tuna. Now i have horrible memory and can't remember what else I usually order but I do remember ordering the pork belly the last time. I thought I should try it and stop ordering the usual steaks/fish. I was a little iffy, and asked the waiter for his opinion and he said it's one of his favorites. Warning him that I'm not as adventurous with my palette as others may be, he said "Don't worry. You've had bacon? Then you've had pork belly." That was something new I learned haha. So I got it and was extremely pleased. Tender and wonderful and flavorful. Just proves to me (and maybe others haha) that no matter how foreign (or not) something may be, it'll probably be damn good here.

    I've also gotten the horseradish salmon medallion. Oh god I love it. It's fresh and has the firmness that at least I love. Still tender enough to fall apart with ease though. It's definitely a unique flavor. It's something I usually get.

    Now the desserts. All yummy. My parents usually get the chocolate souffles, the star dessert. They pour in 2 sauces, chocolate and something white, I don't know cause I'm too engrossed in how good it looks to ever listen to what it is, but man it's heaven. Another good dessert was the one my sister got. Some delicious spin on an apple pie. Louisiana something yummy with ice cream yum yum yum.

    I think you all get my drift. YUM! They also end the night giving the ladies delicious breakfast pastries. They're always a different flavor. Sometimes chocolate, other times a fruity flavor, like pineapple. No matter what, it's all yummy.

    9/19/2008

    Yelp should raise the bar and provide 6 stars instead of 5, as Gary Danko deiniftely deserves a 6-star rating.

    I'm not a regular customer as I've been there only four times in the past 8 years. I would go there only for special occasions.

    I believe that a good restaurant should come in full package, that includes the atmosphere, the quality of food, and service. Gary Danko has topped all three elements in my book and I will explain why.

    I chose this place to propose to my wife back in 2000. I realized that proposing is such an important event in my (and our) life so I made a very careful choice after doing tons of research on the web. I don't want to get into too much detail and try to make the long story short. As soon as I called a month ahead to book the reservation, and stated my intention to propose to my wife, the reservationist immediately gave the phone over to the restaurant manager (or head captain). They carefully noted what my expectations, and gave me some advice. Needless to say, the whole event went smoothly and thanks to the staff member of Gary Danko, to orchestrated everything so well. My wife was very touched and agreed to marry me. I remember receiving a bottle of champagne from an old couple eating at the bar, and a nice plate of chocolate, complimentary from the manager. It was a wonderful feeling.

    Food - Although we've been there only a few times but we have never been disappointed, not a single time. If you watch Iron Chef shows, and it's apparent that you know what good food is supposed to be. The taste, the originality, plating, and presentation. Not a single bit that I can criticize at all. We always try the tasting menu so we can try a little bit of everything, and I suggest you to do the same.

    Service - staff have been very attentive, yet, not intrusive. Whenever you need anything. Before your eye balls start looking around, the wait person is already next to you, but you never get the feeling that you are being "watched" while you're eating. At least I didn't.

    Atmosphere - Okay, here's the tough part. The first two times we went, the place was busy (well, always busy) but the noise level was very low and comfortable. However, the last two times (once in 2005 and the other time was in May 2007) were much noisier than it used to be. I don't know if this bothers you, but I feel more comfortable in eating in a nice restaurant without raising my voice to converse. Having said that, this does NOT cloud my intention to give Gary Danko a 6 star rating.

    Hope this is helpful to you. If you're well off, you should go there often. If you're just like me, a normal working class employee, you should eat there at least once.

    - jcgoobee -

    12/11/2008

    Gary Danko is a very special place. Few restaurants can combine brilliant cuisine, extraordinary service, and such a beautiful environment.

    First, the dishes are lush, beautiful to observe, and thoughtfully prepared. For our last dinner, we began with the glazed oysters. The oysters are tender, and the cavier lends a deeply rich taste that is not heavy, but suprisingly light. We had both a lobster salad with a hazelnut compote, and a roaster lobster over potato with what I beleive was a truffle oil though I may be mistaken. Both were artfully prepared, and the lobster was tender and very flavorful. The dishes wind together classic elements with innovative features, such as the aforementioned hazlenut. Ingredients are very fresh, and the preparations are deceptively complex. Try a green bean off of your plate. Now try one from another dish. Yes, they are very, very different, each matched to the context of the plate they are served on.

    The artful presentation of the food is also delightful. Separate ceramic dishes are used, many finely crafted with striking designs. The food and its presentation are truly an integrated whole. Our belini was serviced on a sparklying black dish that I could have easily made the center piece of a table is was so pleasing to the eye.

    The restaurant itself is a jewel box, with interesting artwork abounding on the walls, and incredible flower arrangement in unusual glass vases. Its simply fun to look around and take in your surroundings.

    Finally, the service is amazing. Small touches you may not notice are present everywhere. For example, when they pour wine, the bottle is *always* held so that you can see the label and know what is moving into your glass. If your date needs to excuse herself/himself as a dish is being set down, they will immediately cover it with a beautiful silver warmer (they'll hold it if its not already placed until she/he returns). The roses on the table are very pretty and add a touch of elegence. The waitstaff lets you take your time with the menu, knows its contents thoroughly, and is friendly and welcoming without crowding you.

    The amazing thing is how effortless this whole process appears, when in fact, it must take the discipline and coordination of a full submarine crew to run the place. Steven Lande, their manager, is a welcoming host. I have no idea how he manages the operation, but whatever he is doing, it works incredibly well. None of the top notch restaurants I've tried in even the most service intensive places (e.g. Hong Kong) can match what his team delivers.

    I should also add that all of my friends here have been made to feel welcome, irrespective of who they are. I was concerned that being in my late twenties when I first tried the restauranta Â few years ago that I might not be treated well--quite the opposite, I was made to feel very welcome. Likewise, my gay friends, asian friends, and african american friends have all felt they received top flight service. Its a place you can take your parents, your wife/girlfriend/partner, or a group of buddies and enjoy a truly terrific dinner. Love it!
